Good. Now we move into one of the most important production concepts.

Without this, Airflow remains only a scheduler.

---

# Topic 10 — Connections in Airflow

# What are Connections?

Connections store external system credentials and connection details inside Apache Airflow.

Used to connect:

* databases
* APIs
* cloud services
* warehouses

---

# Why Connections are Needed

Without connections:

```python id="k4smjt"
username = "admin"
password = "mypassword"
```

Problems:

* hardcoded credentials
* security risks
* poor maintainability

Connections solve this.

---

# Connection Flow

```text id="5w8n6m"
Store Connection in Airflow
            ↓
Access in DAG
            ↓
Connect External System
```

---

# Used For

Connections commonly store:

* PostgreSQL credentials
* MySQL credentials
* AWS access
* API authentication
* SFTP details

---

# Important Rule

## Variables

Used for:

* configuration

---

## Connections

Used for:

* credentials
* authentication
* external systems

---

# Creating Connection

Go to:

```text id="jlwm9l"
Admin → Connections
```

---

# Important Fields

| Field     | Purpose                |
| --------- | ---------------------- |
| Conn Id   | unique connection name |
| Conn Type | database/service type  |
| Host      | server address         |
| Login     | username               |
| Password  | password               |
| Port      | connection port        |
| Schema    | database name          |

---

# Example PostgreSQL Connection

| Field     | Value         |
| --------- | ------------- |
| Conn Id   | postgres_conn |
| Conn Type | PostgreSQL    |
| Host      | postgres      |
| Login     | airflow       |
| Password  | airflow       |
| Port      | 5432          |
| Schema    | airflow       |

---

# Accessing Connections

Airflow operators/hooks use connection IDs.

Example:

```python id="6e2ov4"
postgres_conn
```

---

# What is Conn Id?

Unique identifier used inside DAGs.

Example:

```python id="ef23aj"
postgres_conn
aws_default
mysql_conn
```

---

# Connection Types

| Type                | Used For      |
| ------------------- | ------------- |
| PostgreSQL          | Postgres DB   |
| MySQL               | MySQL DB      |
| HTTP                | APIs          |
| Amazon Web Services | AWS           |
| SFTP                | File transfer |

---

# Real Production Example

```text id="14m7cg"
Airflow DAG
      ↓
PostgreSQL Connection
      ↓
Load Warehouse Data
```

---

# Important Understanding

Connections are centrally managed.

Benefits:

* secure
* reusable
* environment friendly

---

# Test Connection

Airflow UI allows:

* testing connectivity
* validating credentials

Very important during debugging.

---

# Environment Migration

Same DAG can run across:

* dev
* test
* prod

Only connection changes.

DAG code remains same.

This is huge in production engineering.

---

# Connection Security

Better than hardcoding credentials.

Still:

* enterprises use secret managers
* Vault
* AWS Secrets Manager
* Azure Key Vault

---

# Variable vs Connection

| Feature  | Variable      | Connection           |
| -------- | ------------- | -------------------- |
| Purpose  | Config values | External system auth |
| Used For | File paths    | DB/API credentials   |
| Security | Low           | Better               |

---

# Important Industry Reality

A large part of Airflow work is:

* debugging failed connections
* expired credentials
* network issues
* authentication failures

Not just DAG coding.

